; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The important thing to take away f=
rom both pieces is that web3 introduces the opportunity to create software =
infrastructure that is free to use forever, and that anyone can build on to=
p of, but that rewards &#8220;the builders and participants for creating an=
d contributing to these invaluable systems that serve society at large for =
many years to come.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>The most successful exam=
ple to date, which I highlighted last week, is </span><a href=3D"https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/36a63411-cbed-4b93-85b9-feecfb84427c?u=3D16283549" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Uniswap</a><spa=
n>. Despite not charging its users a fee, Uniswap has a $4.1 billion market=
 cap (fully diluted: $5.6 billion). Horne believes that there should be a s=
ingle hyperstructure for each financial and non-financial utility: exchange=
s (Uniswap), marketplaces, lending pools, options, domain names, registries=
, identity, curation, tags, reputation, emojis, read receipts, and more.&#1=
60;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Each would be a piece of free infrastructure, =
composable with other pieces of free infrastructure, that each successive g=
eneration of entrepreneurs can build with, enabling them to focus on the th=
ing that differentiates them, thus increasing the rate of innovation and ab=
undance of creativity. Hyperstructures excite me for the same reason that <=
/span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d9bac660-84f6-4e68-8c7d-f738=
6404a5ae?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: u=
nderline;">APIs excite me</a><span>, with the added benefits of being free,=
 permanent, expansive, and permissionless.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Hyperst=
ructures will underpin a global, liquid market for both digital and physica=
l items.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">As Zach Weinberg highlighted in our debate on De=
Fi and housing, there&#8217;s a lot to figure out to bring real world asset=
s (RWA) online. For one, what happens in the case of default? While default=
s are a rare occurrence that happen on less than 2% of loans, they will sti=
ll need to be settled on paper, in courts. There will need to be hybrid sol=
utions that mirror some analog workflows. But dealing with legacy processes=
 for a small minority of cases in order to make the majority of cases faste=
r, cheaper, more efficient, and more composable is a feature, not a bug.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Personally, I think it&#8217;s inevitable, and I&#821=
7;m going to quote our friend </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b81f37f0-4c74-4940-a357-a57dad33a5b7?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Jeff Bezos</a><span> to explain w=
hy:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; ma=
rgin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em><strong>'What's not going to c=
hange in the next 10 years?'</strong><span> &#8230; [I]n our retail busines=
s, we know that customers want low prices, and I know that's going to be tr=
ue 10 years from now. They want fast delivery; they want vast selection. It=
's impossible to imagine a future 10 years from now where a customer comes =
up and says, 'Jeff I love Amazon; I just wish the prices were a little high=
er,' [or] 'I love Amazon; I just wish you'd deliver a little more slowly.' =
Impossible.</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Customers want </spa=
n><strong>low prices, fast delivery, and vast selection</strong><span>. Web=
3 has the potential to bring all three to financial markets. Whether in ten=
 years, twenty, or thirty, I expect that most large financial assets and tr=
ansactions touch web3 &#8211; whether that&#8217;s houses, cars, project fi=
nance, or company ownership. Bringing those assets on-chain will connect th=
em to global pools of capital and liquidity, and to all of the money legos =
being created in DeFi.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>As </span><a href=3D"=
https://substack.com/redirect/02355787-f555-407b-ad47-786280f05faf?u=3D1628=
3549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Sam Le=
ssin put it</a><span>, &#8220;Most things people own, real estate, small bu=
sinesses, etc. have shit access to liquidity, leverage, etc.&#8221; The pri=
ze for solving that pain point is enormous &#8211; the </span><strong>token=
ization of everything</strong><span> &#8211; and will attract waves of tale=
nt, capital, and creative approaches. Obviously, this will need to be done =
hand-in-hand with smart regulation. When crypto touches RWA &#8211; when sm=
all business owners can source cheaper capital, when homeowners can get mor=
e competitive home equity loans, and when users can seamlessly own a piece =
of the products they use &#8211; regulators will be motivated to find solut=
ions that protect people without restricting access.&#160;</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0=
;">With Hyperstructures, tokenized everything, and rapid iteration on econo=
mic and governance models, web3 will be a big piece of the puzzle in solvin=
g some of humanity&#8217;s most complex challenges.</p><p style=3D"color: #=
1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Phy=
sical&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>The first essay I wrote this year wa=
s called </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4bb9688a-fa7b-=
452d-b740-3ac5d6da1866?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text=
-decoration: underline;">The Laboratory for Complex Problems</a><span>. </s=
pan></em><span>It was about web3&#8217;s opportunity to be a simulator for =
solutions to complex problems that require large-scale human coordination, =
like climate change.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>The theory is simple. All of =
the tokens, voting, and even NFTs are in a </span><strong>goldilocks zone</=
strong><span>: contained enough that the stakes are low for most people, bu=
t with bigger financial consequences than the $20 students play with when t=
hey participate in academic economics studies. Plus, web3 ecosystems are dy=
namic and interconnected, more like the simulations that complexity scienti=
sts run than formulae and theories, with real people instead of &#8220;econ=
omic man.&#8221; Read that piece for the full argument; for now, I&#8217;ll=
 quickly go over two complex problem areas that web3 is starting to tackle =
via </span><strong>regenerative finance</strong><span> and </span><strong>d=
ecentralized science</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Regenerativ=
e Finance. </strong><span>Among the challenges with our current financial s=
ystem is that it&#8217;s too easy to get away with producing negative exter=
nalities and letting the commons foot the bill. Regenerative Finance (ReFi)=
, is a bold attempt to rethink the system. As I wrote in </span><em><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/eabf462e-d761-4310-95e8-053747116434?u=3D=
16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Ce=
lo: Building a Regenerative Economy</a></em><span>:</span></p><blockquote s=
tyle=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: =
#1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left=
: 1em;"><em><span>ReFi is a beautiful idea &#8211; a re-imagining of the fi=
nancial system using the tools humanity now has at its disposal to better a=
ccount for the needs of all stakeholders, current and future. It </span><st=
rong>puts a price on externalities</strong><span>, </span><strong>charging =
those who create negative externalities</strong><span> and </span><strong>r=
ewarding those who create positive externalities</strong><span>.&#160;</spa=
n></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Specific ideas in ReFi include UBI, lendin=
g, data ownership, community commerce, and many web3 x climate projects tha=
